PuTTY source code README
========================

This is the README for the source code of PuTTY, a free Windows, Unix,
and macOS Telnet and SSH client.

PuTTY is built using CMake <https://cmake.org/>. To compile in the
simplest way (on any of Linux, Windows or Mac), the general method is
to run these commands in the source directory:

  cmake .
  cmake --build .

These commands will expect to find a usable compile toolchain on your
path. So if you're building on Windows with MSVC, you'll need to make
sure that the MSVC compiler (cl.exe) is on your path, by running one
of the 'vcvars32.bat' setup scripts provided with the tools. Then the
cmake commands above should work.

To install in the simplest way on Linux or Mac:

  cmake --build . --target install

On Unix, pterm would like to be setuid or setgid, as appropriate, to
permit it to write records of user logins to /var/run/utmp and
/var/log/wtmp. (Of course it will not use this privilege for
anything else, and in particular it will drop all privileges before
starting up complex subsystems like GTK.) The cmake install step
doesn't attempt to add these privileges, so if you want user login
recording to work, you should manually ch{own,grp} and chmod the
pterm binary yourself after installation. If you don't do this,
pterm will still work, but not update the user login databases.

Documentation (in various formats including Windows Help and Unix
`man' pages) is built from the Halibut (`.but') files in the `doc'
subdirectory. If you aren't using one of our source snapshots,
you'll need to do this yourself. Halibut can be found at
<https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/halibut/>.

The PuTTY home web site is

    https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/

If you want to send bug reports or feature requests, please read the
Feedback section of the web site before doing so. Sending one-line
reports saying `it doesn't work' will waste your time as much as
ours.

See the file LICENCE for the licence conditions.

For the native macOS AppKit GUI (PuTTY.app / pterm.app / PuTTYgen.app),
see the section below and the fuller guide in macos/README.md.


Building on macOS (native GUI)
------------------------------

This tree includes a native macOS GUI built with Swift and AppKit
(PuTTY.app, pterm.app, PuTTYgen.app). The phased design notes live in
MACOS_GUI_PLAN.md; day-to-day build/run steps are also in macos/README.md.

Quick start (recommended)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

From the repository root, with Homebrew Bash 5.x on PATH
(`brew install bash`, then ensure `/opt/homebrew/bin` or
`/usr/local/bin` precedes `/bin`):

  ./macos/build.sh check            # verify Xcode / CMake / Ninja / Swift
  ./macos/build.sh --dev            # Debug, host arch → build-macos-gui-dev/
  ./macos/build.sh open --dev       # launch PuTTY.app

Other common invocations:

  ./macos/build.sh --release                 # Release Ninja (host arch)
  ./macos/build.sh --universal               # Universal 2 via Xcode
  ./macos/build.sh open --dev --app pterm
  ./macos/build.sh open --dev --app puttygen
  ./macos/build.sh verify --universal
  ./macos/build.sh install --release --prefix /Applications
  ./macos/build.sh test --dev                # CTest suite (Phase 9.1)
  make test                                  # same via root Makefile
  make test-all                              # CTest + utils self-tests
  ./macos/build.sh --help

Transcripts go to `<build-dir>/build.log` (pass `--no-log` to disable).

Prerequisites
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  - macOS 15 (Sequoia) or later (deployment target)
  - Xcode 16 or later (Swift 6 + macOS 15 SDK)
  - Xcode Command Line Tools, with the active developer directory
    pointing at the full Xcode app (not CLT alone), e.g.:
      xcode-select --install
      sudo xcode-select -s /Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer
  - CMake 3.28 or later
  - Ninja (dev/release profiles) or the Xcode generator (Universal 2)
  - Python 3 (icon generation at build time)
  - Bash 5.x for `macos/build.sh` (`brew install bash`)

GUI build vs CLI / GTK build
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

On Darwin, CMake selects the platform according to PUTTY_MACOS_GUI:

  PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=OFF (default)
      Uses the existing unix/ platform. Builds CLI tools (plink, pscp,
      psftp, …) and, if GTK is found, the legacy GTK-based putty and
      pterm binaries.

  PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON
      Uses the macos/ platform. Builds native AppKit apps (PuTTY.app,
      pterm.app, puttygen.app) plus CLI tools linked against the macos/
      C layer. Does not use GTK.

Use separate build directories for GUI and CLI/GTK builds; do not
reconfigure the same build tree between the two modes.

CMake without the helper script
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Debug / host-arch (fast local iteration):

  cmake -B build-macos-gui-dev -G Ninja \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=OFF \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0
  cmake --build build-macos-gui-dev
  open build-macos-gui-dev/PuTTY.app

Release / host-arch:

  cmake -B build-macos-gui -G Ninja \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=OFF \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0
  cmake --build build-macos-gui

Universal 2 (arm64 + x86_64) requires the Xcode generator:

  cmake -B build-macos-gui-universal -G Xcode \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0
  cmake --build build-macos-gui-universal --config Release
  lipo -info \
    build-macos-gui-universal/Release/PuTTY.app/Contents/MacOS/PuTTY

Ninja cannot produce fat Swift binaries: with Ninja,
PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON warns and builds the host architecture only.

After a GUI build, optional checks:

  cmake --build build-macos-gui --target verify-bundle-layout
  cmake --install build-macos-gui --prefix /Applications

Info.plist version fields are stamped at configure time from version.h /
LATEST.VER / git describe (see macos/cmake/bundle_version.cmake).

CLI-only build on macOS (unchanged)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  ./macos/build.sh --cli
  # or:
  cmake -B build-macos-cli -G Ninja
  cmake --build build-macos-cli

Further reading: macos/README.md (build/run), macos/AGENT.md (SSH agent),
MACOS_GUI_PLAN.md (architecture and remaining packaging work).
